System Design---->
Scaling → The process of managing server traffic and load is called scaling. Basically, it has 2 types:
Vertical Scaling (downtime)
Horizontal Scaling
Vertical Scaling (downtime)
In a running machine, we cannot directly change RAM or CPU, so we need to restart or stop the system for some time. This process is called vertical scaling. In this, we increase the resources (RAM, CPU, storage) of a single server.

========================================================================================================
To solve this problem → Horizontal Scaling is used
In this, instead of making one server bigger, multiple servers are added based on requirement.
Problem:
If the main server has an IP (like 123.67.7), then all requests will come to that server. So how will traffic go to new servers?
Solution → Load Balancer
To solve this problem, a load balancer is used. It controls incoming traffic and distributes it across different servers.
It generally follows the Round Robin algorithm:
If there are 4 servers and 4 requests:
1st request → Server 1
2nd request → Server 2
3rd request → Server 3
4th request → Server 4
In this way, traffic gets evenly distributed.

