api gateway-->
API Gateway is an important part of system design. It handles client requests and routes them to the correct server/service.
An API Gateway acts as a reverse proxy and single entry point for microservices architecture, routing client requests to appropriate backend services, aggregating results, and managing common concerns.
How it works (step-by-step):
1 Single Entry Point (IP / Domain):
The client (web/app) hits only one endpoint, like:
http://10.5.8.2 or api.example.com
Behind this IP/Domain, there is an API Gateway.
2 Request Receive & Check:
The gateway first receives the request and checks:
URL path (/auth, /orders, /payments)
Headers (token, auth, etc.)
Method (GET, POST, etc.)
3 Authentication & Security:
It verifies the token (whether login is valid or not)
It blocks unauthorized requests here itself
4 Routing (Main work):
The gateway decides where the request should go:
/auth → Auth Service
/orders → Order Service
/payments → Payment Service
5 Works with Load Balancer:
If a service has multiple servers, then Gateway + Load Balancer together decide which server will handle the request.
For example, if there are 3 Order servers, traffic will be distributed among all of them (Round Robin, etc.)
6 Sending response back:
The response received from the service is sent back to the client by the gateway.
Note-->
Client → API Gateway (IP: 10.5.8.2) → Load Balancer → Service (Auth/Order/Payment) → Response → Client
Short
API Gateway is a “gate” through which all requests pass
It secures, routes, and manages requests
And works with Load Balancer to efficiently distribute traffic across multiple servers

