Microservices Communication →
To create communication between two microservices, synchronous or asynchronous (event/queue) methods are used.
Synchronous →
In this, one service calls another service and waits until the response is received.
Problem:
The user has to wait and the system becomes slow.
Example:
If after payment, an email needs to be sent →
First payment happens
Then Payment Service calls Email Service through Load Balancer
Only after the email is sent, the response is returned
If multiple users make payments at the same time, sending emails will take time and the whole system becomes slow
Asynchronous (Queue) →
To solve this problem, an asynchronous approach is used where a queue is used
As soon as payment happens, an event/message is added to the queue
Email Worker (consumer) picks the message from the queue
Then it sends the email
In this, Payment Service does not need to wait and it immediately returns the response
FIFO (First In First Out)
The payment that happens first will have its email sent first
Poll Function →
In this, Email Worker repeatedly asks Payment Service:
Is there any new payment?
Push →
In this, Payment Service directly informs the Email Worker/queue:
please send email
This approach is fast and efficient
Note →
There is still one problem that it mostly works in one-to-one communication
Example:
After payment →
Message should go to WhatsApp
Email should also be sent
SMS should also be sent to contact number
If we inform each service separately, the system becomes complex
Solution → Pub/Sub Model (Event Driven Architecture)
To solve this problem, Publish-Subscribe model is used
Payment Service publishes an event (Payment Success)
This event goes to a common system (queue/broker)
Multiple services (Email, SMS, WhatsApp) subscribe to it and receive it
This means once the event is published, all microservices automatically consume it
→
One-to-One (complex & tightly coupled)
Pub/Sub (scalable & loosely coupled)
This approach is called Event-Driven Architecture